      "note" : [ {
        "text" : "Before the Taliban took over the country, Afghan women lived under fairly progressive conditions, especially in urban centers. They received the right to vote in 1919. The practice of “purdah,” or gender segregation in the home and in public, was abolished in the 1950s. Until the 1970s, women would routinely be seen in public without a veil, and miniskirts were a common sight in Kabul.",
